WEBVTT

00:05.300 --> 00:06.300 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Good evening.

00:06.300 --> 00:07.300 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
I'm Judy Woodruff.

00:07.300 --> 00:09.366 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
On the "NewsHour" tonight:

00:09.366 --> 00:10.000 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
DONALD TRUMP, President of
the United States: I would say
I'm disappointed in what took

00:10.000 --> 00:11.933 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
place.

00:11.933 --> 00:14.533 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: The
showdown over health care
reaches a fever pitch.

00:14.533 --> 00:19.533 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
President Trump slams Senate
Republicans, who can't win
enough support to replace or

00:20.400 --> 00:22.300 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
repeal the Affordable Care Act.

00:22.300 --> 00:26.366 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
Then: another Obama-era
legacy left standing.

00:26.366 --> 00:31.366 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
The Trump administration
reluctantly certifies
Iran's compliance with
the nuclear deal, but

00:32.800 --> 00:35.600 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
adds new sanctions over its
ballistic missile program.

00:35.600 --> 00:37.933 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
And defying the odds.

00:37.933 --> 00:42.933 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
An all-girls team from
Afghanistan competes
in a robotics contest
after being denied entry

00:44.700 --> 00:47.233 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
into the U.S. twice.

00:47.233 --> 00:49.833 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
FATEMAH QADERYAN, Student
(through translator): I
want to show the world
what Afghan girls,

00:49.833 --> 00:51.666 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
or young girls, can do.

00:51.666 --> 00:55.133 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
We can show them, when we have
a creative idea, we can do it.

00:55.133 --> 00:58.700 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: All that and more
on tonight's "PBS NewsHour."

00:58.700 --> 01:02.866 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
(BREAK)

01:02.866 --> 01:07.866 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: The latest Senate
Republican push to replace
the Affordable Care Act has

01:15.000 --> 01:16.600 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
come to nothing.

01:16.600 --> 01:20.133 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Now party leaders say they
will try for just repeal.

01:20.133 --> 01:23.866 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
Lisa Desjardins begins
our coverage of the past
tumultuous 24 hours.

01:23.866 --> 01:25.900 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
SEN.

01:25.900 --> 01:28.233 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MITCH MCCONNELL (R-KY), Majority
Leader: I regret that the
effort to repeal and immediately

01:28.233 --> 01:32.533 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
replace the failures
of Obamacare will
not be successful.

01:32.533 --> 01:37.533 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
LISA DESJARDINS: A remarkable
statement and a bitter admission
for Senate Majority Leader

01:39.500 --> 01:42.533 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
Mitch McConnell, that
Republicans still can't
muster the votes on
a health care bill.

01:44.500 --> 01:47.666 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It became clear last night,
after Utah's Mike Lee and Jerry
Moran of Kansas said they'd

01:48.633 --> 01:50.566 align:left position:25%,start line:86.67% size:75%
vote against the
revised version.

01:50.566 --> 01:53.700 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
With that, McConnell
changed course, and decided
to go for pure repeal.

01:53.700 --> 01:55.866 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
SEN.

01:55.866 --> 01:57.533 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MITCH MCCONNELL: A majority
of the Senate voted to pass
the same repeal legislation

01:57.533 --> 02:00.500 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
back in 2015.

02:00.500 --> 02:03.066 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
President Obama vetoed it then.

02:03.066 --> 02:06.500 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
President Trump -- President
Trump will sign it now.

02:06.500 --> 02:11.500 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
LISA DESJARDINS: McConnell
proposed delaying the effective
date of repeal for two years,

02:12.633 --> 02:14.666 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
so both parties can
work out a replacement.

02:14.666 --> 02:19.500 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But, almost immediately, three
Republicans came out as no's
to McConnell's idea That's

02:20.333 --> 02:22.833 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
enough to kill it.

02:22.833 --> 02:26.600 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Lisa Murkowski of Alaska,
Shelley Moore Capito
of West Virginia, and
Susan Collins of Maine

02:26.600 --> 02:31.366 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
all said it is too risky
to repeal without an
immediate plan for what next.

02:31.366 --> 02:33.433 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
SEN.

02:33.433 --> 02:37.366 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
SUSAN COLLINS (R), Maine: I
do not think it is going to be
constructive to repeal a law

02:39.300 --> 02:43.100 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
that, at this point, is so
interwoven in our health care
system, and then hope that, over

02:45.933 --> 02:50.166 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
the next two years, we
will come up with some
kind of replacement.

02:50.166 --> 02:55.166 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
LISA DESJARDINS: At the same
time, Democrats are flexing
their muscles against repeal.

02:55.166 --> 02:56.233 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Minority Leader Chuck Schumer:

02:56.233 --> 02:58.433 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
SEN.

02:58.433 --> 03:02.233 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
CHUCK SCHUMER (D-NY),
Minority Leader: Passing
repeal now is not a door
to bipartisan solutions,

03:03.400 --> 03:05.100 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
as the majority leader
suggested this morning.

03:05.100 --> 03:08.000 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Rather, it is a disaster.

03:08.000 --> 03:11.666 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
The door to bipartisanship
is open right now.

03:11.666 --> 03:16.666 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Not with repeal, but
with an effort to improve
the existing system.

03:19.133 --> 03:21.100 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
LISA DESJARDINS: Even
though it seems certain
to fail, Republican
leaders said they're going

03:21.100 --> 03:24.100 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
to press forward and hold
a vote some time soon.

03:24.100 --> 03:25.766 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
SEN.

03:25.766 --> 03:27.933 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
MITCH MCCONNELL: Well,
I think we will have
to see what happens.

03:27.933 --> 03:32.933 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
We will have demonstrated that
Republicans by themselves are
not prepared at this point

03:36.366 --> 03:38.066 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
to do a replacement.

03:38.066 --> 03:39.400 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
DONALD TRUMP, President
of the United States:
We're not going own it.

03:39.400 --> 03:41.433 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
I'm not going to own it.

03:41.433 --> 03:43.533 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
LISA DESJARDINS: At the White
House, President Trump was left
lamenting the latest health

03:43.533 --> 03:46.766 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
care failure, and insisting
the fault lies elsewhere.

03:46.766 --> 03:51.333 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
DONALD TRUMP: For seven years,
I have been hearing repeal
and replace from Congress.

03:51.333 --> 03:53.400 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
And I have been hearing
it loud and strong.

03:53.400 --> 03:57.700 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And then, when we finally get
a chance to repeal and replace,
they don't take advantage

03:57.700 --> 03:59.800 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
of it.

03:59.800 --> 04:02.300 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
We will let Obamacare fail, and
then the Democrats are going
to come to us and they're going

04:02.300 --> 04:04.500 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
to say, how do we fix
it, how do we fix it?

04:04.500 --> 04:09.500 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
LISA DESJARDINS: As recently
as yesterday, Mr. Trump sounded
more confident, in a quick

04:10.366 --> 04:11.633 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
aside to Vice President Pence.

04:11.633 --> 04:13.833 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
DONALD TRUMP: We're
getting it together.

04:13.833 --> 04:16.466 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
And it's going to
happen, right, Mike?

04:16.466 --> 04:18.400 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
MIKE PENCE, Vice President of
the United States: Yes, sir.

04:18.400 --> 04:19.400 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
DONALD TRUMP: I think.

04:19.400 --> 04:21.466 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(APPLAUSE)

04:21.466 --> 04:24.333 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
LISA DESJARDINS: Mr. Trump has
repeatedly said he's willing
to sign a repeal-only bill.

04:24.333 --> 04:28.800 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The vice president, who spent
much of the day on Capitol
Hill, urged lawmakers to do

04:28.800 --> 04:30.033 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
something.

04:30.033 --> 04:32.533 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
MIKE PENCE: Inaction
is not an option.

04:32.533 --> 04:34.733 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Congress needs to step up.

04:34.733 --> 04:39.733 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Congress needs to do
their job, and Congress
needs to do their job now.

04:42.200 --> 04:44.833 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
LISA DESJARDINS: House
Speaker Paul Ryan sounded
a similar note, and also
said the House bill,

04:47.333 --> 04:49.900 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
which repeals and replaces
Obamacare simultaneously,
is still -- quote --
"the best way to go."

04:50.433 --> 04:52.500 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
REP.

04:52.500 --> 04:54.533 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
PAUL RYAN (R-WI), Speaker of the
House: Well, we'd like to see
the Senate move on something.

04:54.533 --> 04:57.233 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
LISA DESJARDINS: And House
Budget Committee Chair Diane
Black joined the chorus urging

04:57.233 --> 04:58.233 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
the Senate to act.

04:58.233 --> 05:00.366 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
REP.

05:00.366 --> 05:01.300 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
DIANE BLACK (R), Tennessee:
We're going to be eternally
optimistic that the Senate is

05:01.300 --> 05:03.400 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
going to get their work done.

05:03.400 --> 05:07.533 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
LISA DESJARDINS: Meanwhile, a
bipartisan group of 11 governors
called for the Senate to reject

05:07.533 --> 05:11.500 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
efforts to repeal Obamacare
now and replace it later.

05:11.500 --> 05:14.633 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
So, when we will see the
next votes in the Senate?

05:14.633 --> 05:18.300 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Senator John Cornyn, the number
two Republican in the Senate,
told my colleague Ellis Kim

05:18.300 --> 05:21.933 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
(ph) and some other reporters
tonight he expects that
vote this week -- Judy.

05:21.933 --> 05:25.033 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: And, Lisa,
from what you're reporting, it
doesn't sound like they have

05:25.033 --> 05:28.300 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
the votes to pass
repeal, so what are they
going to do after that?

05:28.300 --> 05:30.366 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
LISA DESJARDINS: Right,
it's fascinating.

05:30.366 --> 05:34.433 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
They're frantic to take a vote
now that likely will fail and
looks it like, Judy, after that,

05:36.433 --> 05:39.366 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
they're ready for a
180-degree turn to move
from this closed-door
process they have had

05:39.366 --> 05:44.166 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
until now for the past seven
months to a more open, public,
kind of regular process that,

05:44.166 --> 05:46.966 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
as it's known here in the
Senate, with committee hearings.

05:46.966 --> 05:51.466 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Late tonight, the chairman
of the Health Committee
here in the Senate, Senator
Alexander, announced

05:51.466 --> 05:56.200 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
he does plan to holding
open hearings on health
care and stabilizing
the markets, regardless

05:56.200 --> 05:58.233 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
of the vote.

05:58.233 --> 06:00.433 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And, Judy, it's worth noting
those three senators who are the
no votes, who are essentially

06:00.433 --> 06:05.400 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
blocking this latest effort from
Mr. McConnell, they're are all
senators who were not included

06:06.266 --> 06:08.266 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
in the closed-door meetings.

06:08.266 --> 06:11.033 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Those female senators now
saying they think it should have
been open like this all along.

06:11.033 --> 06:15.733 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
JUDY WOODRUFF: So,
Lisa, this is a big
hit for the Republicans
in the Senate and the

06:15.733 --> 06:16.966 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Congress overall.

06:16.966 --> 06:18.200 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
What are they saying to you?

06:18.200 --> 06:19.533 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
How do they feel about this?

06:19.533 --> 06:21.133 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
LISA DESJARDINS:
They're very raw, Judy.

06:21.133 --> 06:24.200 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
One of them told me that
they're just exhausted.

06:24.200 --> 06:27.900 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Another said today's meeting
of all Republican senators
was -- quote -- "robust."

06:27.900 --> 06:30.600 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
Translation of that,
Judy, it was tense.

06:30.600 --> 06:33.933 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
There is some real fear
about what this means for
their elections next year.

06:33.933 --> 06:38.033 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
There are real questions
about what it means to hold a
vote that is likely to fail.

06:38.033 --> 06:39.500 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Why are they doing that?

06:39.500 --> 06:41.700 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
Why does Mitch McConnell
want to hold the vote?

06:41.700 --> 06:46.700 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Well, the theory is that he
wants to show who is to blame
for blocking their repeal

06:48.633 --> 06:51.566 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
efforts and to say they gave
it their best try, but that
idea could, of course, ricochet

06:51.566 --> 06:53.633 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
and harm some of their
senators as well.

06:53.633 --> 06:57.333 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: So, what about
Majority Leader McConnell?

06:57.333 --> 06:59.966 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
Is his standing
secure after all this?

06:59.966 --> 07:03.400 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
LISA DESJARDINS: Well,
one senator, Ron Johnson
of Wisconsin, made an
extraordinary statement

07:03.400 --> 07:07.933 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
today, saying he doesn't have
confidence in Mitch McConnell
anymore and doesn't trust

07:07.933 --> 07:08.933 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
his leadership.

07:08.933 --> 07:11.000 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
But, Judy, he was an exception.

07:11.000 --> 07:14.666 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Other senators, including
Lisa Murkowski, told me they
do have confidence in him.

07:14.666 --> 07:16.733 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
She gave a great quote
today, Judy, to us.

07:16.733 --> 07:21.133 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
She said that Mitch McConnell
is trying to keep the frogs
in the wheelbarrow and doing

07:21.133 --> 07:23.200 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
as well as he can.

07:23.200 --> 07:26.166 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Fascinating, because she's one
of the frogs that actually has
jumped out of that wheelbarrow,

07:26.166 --> 07:31.166 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
but it looks like for now
his leadership will stay
and he will stay in power.

07:32.333 --> 07:33.633 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
JUDY WOODRUFF: I
like the metaphor.

07:33.633 --> 07:37.133 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
Lisa, what does all this
mean for health care?

07:37.133 --> 07:42.000 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Because the Republicans have run
several plans up the flagpole.

07:42.000 --> 07:43.933 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
They haven't passed.

07:43.933 --> 07:44.933 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Where do they stand?

07:44.933 --> 07:45.933 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Where do we stand?

07:45.933 --> 07:47.833 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
LISA DESJARDINS: That's right.

07:47.833 --> 07:49.233 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
This was the fifth draft, maybe
the sixth draft, depending
on how you count it this

07:49.233 --> 07:51.200 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
year.

07:51.200 --> 07:53.400 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Let's just get to some
bottom lines for what we're
doling with now as Americans.

07:53.400 --> 07:58.400 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It looks like now the effort to
have massive Medicaid reform,
large-scale cuts in the numbers

08:00.100 --> 08:02.133 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
of Medicaid recipients
in the future, that
effort now seems dead.

08:02.133 --> 08:05.900 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
However, the fate of
the Medicaid expansion
under Medicaid -- under
the Obamacare, that

08:08.933 --> 08:10.200 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
is not clear.

08:10.200 --> 08:11.766 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
We will have to see what
happens in negotiations.

08:11.766 --> 08:16.100 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
But, overall, Medicaid itself
will largely stay as it is now.

08:16.100 --> 08:21.100 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Also, the idea of repealing
Obamacare wholesale, that
seems unlikely to happen.

08:23.033 --> 08:25.633 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
We will see what happens in
the next vote but it seems most
likely, Judy, that Obamacare

08:25.633 --> 08:30.633 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
will stay largely within the
framework it has now and that
the discussion will shift

08:32.200 --> 08:34.466 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
to how to fix it and
how to stabilize markets
within that framework.

08:34.466 --> 08:38.733 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: And this -- you
and I were talking earlier,
this will have an effect

08:38.733 --> 08:42.400 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
on the larger Republican
leadership agenda as well.

08:42.400 --> 08:45.900 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
LISA DESJARDINS:
Oh, a huge effect.

08:45.900 --> 08:50.100 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
They're hoping that it will not
be catastrophic, but now they
are jammed up against some very,

